Name: George Pickerill
Notes:
Birthday: 0/0/00
Anniversary: 0/0/00
Comments: Met with Yousef and George 1/4/99



As Director of materials George was extremely helpful with very useful  information.



SMT unlimited does about $20 million per year. That amount includes the cost of the components on the boards they stuff.



When I described the concept to him the first thing out of his mouth was what about:



 - Return priviliges.

 - Cancelation priviliges.

 - Restocking priviliges.



His main point was that price was probably 3rd or 4th on the list of importance when procuring parts after many of the following:



 1) On time delivery. 

 2) Warrantee

 3) Return priviliges.

 4) Cancellation priviliges.

 5) Single vendor.

 6) Ease of procurement.



We seem to be bucking a trend which is that Small CMs want to develop deeper and broader relationships with distributors:



Avnet is starting to focus on Small and mid CMs. They have an account rep dedicated to SMT Unlimited this account rep has only six other accounts.



George is trying to find ways to partner more closely and broadly with Avnet.



Avnet can take an entire BOM and quote it. When I asked George what about a service that would take his BOM and have it quoted by several distributors and combine the responding data in a clear and informative way he was luke warm. He said that he suspected price variations would be small in comparison to the benefit of having a single vendor to deal with. It would take significant price differences before he would look elsewhere for a few parts.



Avnet is helping CMs combine their common parts across several boards to get better volume orders.



Avnet has great service and delivery. 



Avnet can take MRP runs directly and provide CM with stock. SMT uses Macola MRP software.



Since its recent acquistions Avnet covers 95% of the parts of their top customers.



Direct stocking is the way of the future. Distributor simply replenishes low items automatically at the clients facility. In large CMs this is turning into in house stores and inhouse warehousing by distributors.



Price is low on the list compared to service. Especially now in conditions of part scarcity and high demand. In fact now there are  brokers who stock parts speculatively and sell to the highest bidder. 15cent tantalum caps are going for $2. 



What kind of things would be helpfull for George. Tools that would combine parts usage across several boards on the line to get better prices for volume orders. One difficulty is approved vendor lists from different OEM clients dont necessarily match up.



Quotes are a big pain.

Name: Gordon Willis
Notes:
Gordon Willis, PhD, is Cognitive Psychologist in the Office of the Associate Director of the Applied Research Program. Prior to that he was Senior Research Methodologist at Research Triangle Institute, and he also worked for over a decade at the National Center for Health Statistics, CDC, to develop methods for developing and testing survey questions.

Dr. Willis attended Oberlin College, and received a PhD in Cognitive Psychology from Northwestern University. He now works mainly in the area of the development and evaluation of surveys on cancer risk factors, and focuses on questionnaire pretesting. He has produced the "Questionnaire Appraisal System" for use in evaluating draft survey questions, and has written the book "Cognitive Interviewing: A Tool for Improving Questionnaire Design." He also co-teaches a graduate-level questionnaire design course at the Joint Program for Survey Methodology at the University of Maryland, and serves as Adjunct Faculty at the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences (USUHS). His research interests have recently turned to cross-cultural issues in self-report surveys and research studies, and in particular the development of best practices for questionnaire translation, and the development of pretesting techniques to evaluate the cross-cultural comparability of survey questions.

Dr. Willis also works in the area of human subjects protection in cancer research, and has served as Chair of the NCI Special Studies Institutional Review Board (IRB). He is a member of the Editorial Board of the Journal of Empirical Research on Human Research Ethics, and consults regularly on matters pertaining to ethical issues in population-based research.

Design rules - Component placement (not such a big deal) because most machines are the same.

Price and availablity of components 



What might be cheapest for one CM is not necessarily cheapest for another.



One idea is a tool that allows you to optimize the design across several CMs allowing you to postpone the decision on choosing a CM.



Instant quotes are not very good or accurate, though many claim to have them.





Purchasing is a massively "tactical activity".
